commit.message:
Fix compiler warnings and a subtle precedence error

Most of the warnings are due to -Wunused-but-set-variable, one is due to
-Wdiscarded-qualifiers.
There are couple due to -Wparentheses. Those are noteworthy as the
default precedence w/o the missing paranthesis is not what we want.

e.g.,
We have : 4 - count & 0x03
We want : 4 - (count & 0x03)
We get  : (4 - count) & 0x03

This is because '-' operator has higher precedence than '&' and they
have left-to-right associativity.

Luckily, for the case (count & 0x03), the incorrect precedence also
results in the same result, so it should not affect anything.

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

Add an example of multithreading with async calls

Example of using multithreading and the async api to copy a file
to an nfs server.

This example will create 4 service threads that will service
the socket, i.e. reading/writing to the socket (as well as executing the
async callbacks).

The example program then creates multiple worker threads, each handling
a 10MByte section of the file to be copied.
Each thread will immediately issue async pwrite calls for the entire section
and then wait until all the callbacks have completed.
The threads issue the async calls concurrently and will result in an
enormous number of concurrent calls being issued to the server.
Some servers have been known to crash once you go above a few hundred
thousandis of concurrent I/Os.

As these are async calls, the callbacks will execute in the context of the
service context, which means you need to keep the callbacks light-weight
or you may need to increate the number of contexts/service threads.
This is different from when using the sync api where most of the processing
will happen in the worker thread once the responce has been received from
the server.

commit.message: PS3: initialize addrinfo struct

Simplify the optimization to write a pdu directly to the socket

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

nfs-pthreads-writefile: add example of multi-threading/multi-context

Add an example of how to use multithreading tgether with multi-contexts.
To compile this example you need to configure the build with:
./configure --enable-examples --enable-pthread

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

rpc_read_from_socket: move buf to be a member of the rpc context

Do not use a static/global buf pointer as this will break when
using multiple concurrent contexts.

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

rpc_read_from_socket: move pdu_size to be a rpc_context member

Do not use a static variable for pdu_size as that breaks having multiple
different contexts at once.
Move it to be a private member of the rpc_context structure instead.

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

Fix bug in skipping of partially sent iov data

When skipping partially sent iov, num_done must be cleared after
all previously sent data is skipped, else it will cause more data
to be skipped from the next vector.

If mounting v3 fails, try mounting v4 instead

If we did not specify a specific version of nfs, then first try v3 and
if that fails try v4 instead.
Only do this if no version was specified, IF a version was specified then
only that version will fail and there will be no fall-back to a different
version.

Only implement for the sync API for now.

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

Check for memory allocation failures during v3/4 mount_async

Signed-off-by: Ronnie Sahlberg <ronniesahlberg@gmail.com>

Fix segv for UDP packets (broadcast portmap/callit)

This broke recently in the re-factoring to add zero copy reads
and where we broke out the XID value into a new field in the rpc structure.

Assign the xid value properly when reading a UDP packet and check that
we could match the incoming PDU to a request in flight.
